The '''Bakhtiari rug''', along with other weavings, is a major artform of the [[Bakhtiari people|Bakhtiari tribe]], located in [[Chahar Mahaal and Bakhtiari]], [[Iran]].<ref>{{Cite book|author=MacDonald, Brian W.|year=1997|title=Tribal Rugs: Treasures of the Black Tent|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk, England|pages=281&ndash;282|isbn=978-1-85149-268-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=Campbell, Gordon|year=2006|title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Decorative Arts, Volume 1, Aalto to Kyoto pottery|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=i3Od9bcGus0C&pg=PA198 198]|isbn=978-0-19-518948-3}}</ref> They have been weaving rugs exported around the globe since the early 19th century.
== Geography == While originally woven by nomadic Bakhtiari,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Double-bag (khorjin), front, Bakhtiari tribe, Iran, 19th or 20th century |publisher=The Textile Museum |location=Washington, DC |url=http://www.textilemuseum.org/exhibitions/current/TimbuktutoTibet/image4_TTT.htm |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913183428/http://www.textilemuseum.org/exhibitions/current/TimbuktutoTibet/image4_TTT.htm |archivedate=September 13, 2012 }}</ref> most authentic Bakhtiari rugs are woven in Bakhtiari settled communities in west central Iran southwest of Isfahan, [[Chahar Mahaal and Bakhtiari]] and parts of the provinces of [[Isfahan Province|Isfahan]], [[Lorestan]], and eastern [[Khuzestan]], most notably in the town of [[Shahr-Kurd]].<ref name="Farhangsara">{{Cite web|title=Carpet Gallery: Bakhtiari |publisher=Farhangsara |url=http://www.farhangsara.com/carpet_gallery_bakhtiari.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226022043/http://www.farhangsara.com/carpet_gallery_bakhtiari.htm|archivedate=26 February 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Bakhtiari rugs were also known after their place of origin, such as [[Saman, Chaharmahal and Bakhtiari|Saman]] or [[Hureh, Chaharmahal and Bakhtiari|Hureh]] (Hori).<ref name="Farhangsara" /> However, Bakhtiari patterns are copied in other weaving centers in Iran, Pakistan, India and China; so that a place name came to be used to refer to the place of origin of the pattern and quality of the rug, rather than to its place of actual manufacture. Saman and Hori are now regarded as grades of Bakhtiari rugs, rather than as geographical terms.
== Structure == Bakhtiari carpets are based on a cotton foundation ([[Warp (weaving)|warp]]) with a wool [[weft]]<ref>{{Cite book|author=Jerrehian, Aram|year=1990|title=Oriental Rug Primer: Buying and Understanding New Oriental Rugs|publisher=Running Press|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|page=149|isbn=978-0-89471-739-0}}</ref> usually taken from the herds of the producing tribe. This leads to unique carpets that differ depending on the characteristics of each tribe’s wool. The wool can range from dull to extreme glossy and the resultant pile is clipped medium to high. The best carpets with the highest [[knot density]] are often known as ''Bibibaff''.<ref>The word ''baff'' means knot and ''bibi'' is the name for a respected grandmother, hence "skilled". See {{Cite web|title=Carpet glossary: A-C: Bibibaff |url=http://www.carpetencyclopedia.com/pages/Glossary/A_C-310.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225173459/http://www.carpetencyclopedia.com/pages/Glossary/A_C-310.html |archivedate=25 February 2015 |deadurl=no}}</ref> Prices range considerably with the highest knot density rugs generally being the most expensive, but price is also affected by criteria such as the pattern and the dyes used. ''Chapel Shotur'' and ''Saman'' pieces are rated slightly beneath ''Bibibaff'' productions, but are still considered to be good to excellent. ''Hori'' carpets are of looser weave and inferior quality and as such, are generally widely affordable.
The sizes vary from narrow hall carpets to large room designs, often up to 4&nbsp;m&nbsp;×&nbsp;5&nbsp;m. The larger rugs tend to be very rare and harder to come by. Similarly, older rugs, often coveted by collectors, can be extremely costly.
== Patterns == Patterns are usually floral or garden inspired. The ''Khesti'', an established garden motif is perhaps the most well-known rug design. The carpet is divided into individual squares with animals and plants acting as symbols. Another influential design features a decorated field with lattice designs and floral ornaments.
== Colors == The use of colors varies depending on styles of certain tribes. Generally they include shades of white, reds, browns, greens, and yellows. Blue does not appear to feature.{{fact|date=October 2015}} Natural dyes produce variations in color, which are particularly obvious on older Bibibaffs.
