:''Not to be confused with "[[Paris syndrome|Paris Syndrome]]"''

The '''Paris effect''' is a sensation or feeling that heightens the enjoyment of a taste or smell of a food or beverage based on the circumstances of its consumption. It is named for [[Paris, France]].

==History==
The effect was observed by [[Little Caesars Pizza]] founder Jim Savoy, an organic chemist who owned a [[pizza]] parlor in [[Blacksburg, Virginia]]. After selling the parlor to a group of investors, he became a wine merchant, and — at gatherings with fellow [[oenophile]]s — noticed that multiple wines manifested this phenomenon. When the drinker drank a wine they had previously drank in an exotic locale, that experience {{which|date=July 2016}} always rated higher than the present circumstances.

==Further reading==
*[http://www.thepariseffect.net/blog/category/wine Blog] detailing the "Paris effect"

